Of course kind of interesting if you think about it.  Instead of killing avatar of war for some nice item you kill him and 3 other bosses for trade skill stuff that you then have a tradeskiller combine to make into an item <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=targonis>Targonis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 791<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/22/03 10:26 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: E3 EQ2 Video</span><hr size=1> The idea that tradeskill created items should be the most powerful isn't new, but at the same time, it SHOULD be balanced.<br>
<br>
If you kill something, unless their weapons and armor get damaged or destroyed in the battle, there's no reason there shouldn't be a way to loot the items they had.  This is really the flaw I see in MANY games.  <br>
<br>
Also, magic items should NOT be overly common.  In Dungeons and Dragons terms, a +1 piece of armor will NOT be common.  To put it in EQ terms, it should take people until level 20 to even get ONE piece of magic armor, and that would be off a leader.  To get a minor magical  piece of armor for all the different slots MIGHT take until level 35.  It would take killing something fairly serious to get something good, but at the same time, by the time you are killing harder enemies, the minor magic items will become a &quot;junk&quot; drop.<br>
<br>
EQ suffers from too few types of enchantments on the different types of equipment as well.  If you look at what armor should have as possible &quot;enchantments&quot;, you will see:<br>
<br>
Extra protection(AC boost)<br>
<br>
Absorb extra damage<br>
<br>
Stat benefits<br>
<br>
Damage avoidance(the armor would help you move out of the way of a blow)<br>
<br>
What we think of as focus effects, including combat ability boosts, skill boosts, etc...<br>
<br>
Extra offensive ability(if armor can help you avoid being HIT, not just damaged, it might be able to assist in your offensive abilities as well)<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, ANY combination of these abilities, including multiple  of a given type SHOULD be a possibility if someone takes the time to make the item.  From the EQ manual, the knowledge to enchant items was lost, which is why players can't make magic weapons and armor, or at least, in the original EQ.  Verant added stuff to the tradeskills, but never came up with any sort of storyline to say that the lost knowledge on magic item creation is being rediscovered.  <br>
<br>
So, tradeskill created items being the best SHOULD be the way of it, but items won through combat MAY also be magic.  Remember that if a mob were to drop a suit of plate armor, how many of these things can anyone carry in their backpack, or strapped to their back while trudging through a dungeon?  THAT would be a way to limit how much of this &quot;junk&quot; gets into the hands of the players.  <br>
