<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=172233">Camrael's equipment</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=camrael>camrael</A> at: 6/23/03 7:49 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kaelonxerxentis>Kaelon Xerxentis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 179<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/23/03 12:22 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: E3 EQ2 Video</span><hr size=1> I agree with Whizbang, on both counts mentioned above. I think it's unlikely that we'll be seeing EverQuest II anytime soon.<br>
<br>
But that being said - and though I'm not usually one to criticize - I think we're in for some very uncertain times with EverQuest II. None of the original EQ design team (unless if you count SOE exec John Smedley as part of the 'design' team) are on board with EverQuest II, signalling a serious loss of creative talent. Though Sony can most certainly muster the artistic and technical talent that wowed audiences in the first days of EverQuest, what initially drew people to EverQuest was its immersive world, extensive realism and outrageous depth. These were things that purists like Brad McQuaid and Jeff Buttler were dedicated to prioritizing over the concerns of the players and with little regard to the market. The end result defies commerce: it worked remarkably well.<br>
<br>
Now, SOE is in an extremely difficult competition with the award-winning design team at Blizzard, who, unlike Sony, is entering the next generation of MMORPGs with a full ship of its original designers and concept engineers, accompanied by their veteran artists and technicians. The competition is likely to result in some poor design choices, and though I fully support the idea of a Trademaster in EverQuest II, I think it will be extremely difficult for SOE to successfully find a proper balance with respect to the proportional risk vs. reward model that they have so cherished thus far. <br>
<br>
On a side note, Targonis, you really should not unfairly criticize the EverQuest servers, given that the problem has never really been the hardware, but the antiquated software upon which EverQuest's server technology is based. Visit <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.eqemu.net">EQemu</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> sometime, and you'd easily note that even top machines running EQ server emulators are unable to sustain but a dozen or so players on a few zones before crashing. <br>
